Hmmh. Actually. I take it back. I wish there was a comment there, but I suspect reason was/is is that since there is alternate constructor:

```java
    protected StdDeserializer(Class<?> vc) {
        _valueClass = vc;
    }
```

then one that takes `JavaType` should never get `null`.
Basically one should always indicate at least raw type deserializer handles (although granted other constructor should also have `null` check to enforce this).

I am not necessarily 100% against adding back the check due to backwards compatibility aspects -- 3.0 development is starting and this is probably better place to add stricter checks, all things considered -- but at this point I would recommend changing code to actually pass a non-null value like `Object.class` (or, ideally, if more specific type is known, that).

@mehmetsalgar , Spring HATEOAS is based on Jackson 2.8.5 for Spring 4, and 2.9.1 for Spring 5. When you mention Jackson 2.6, not sure what to say there.

If you have a bit of code we can use to capture this regression, we could pinpoint the exact bug and either patch Spring HATEOAS or provide better feedback to the Jackson team.

(I @'d the wrong person. Sorry @cowtowncoder !)

@gregturn I think original submitted mentioned 2.6 as the version he was using. But I think same conditions apply up until 2.8.x.

Change in question is in 2.9, removal of one `null` check. I may bring that back, but fundamentally I think calling code (sub-class of `StdDeserializer`) should probably be changed so that instead of calling 

    public StdDeserializer(JavaType t)

with `null`, it should call

    public StdDeserializer(Class<?> type)

with non-null value (if not known, `Object.class`) is fine. Passing `null` would probably not fail either and would be improvement as well.

So what I was hoping was to suggest a minor improvement since passing of `null` as `JavaType` is probably going to disappear from later versions.

Does this make more sense? Apologies for not giving enough context.
